@@eRakuen: The Failed Paradise@@N

South of Midgaard, beyond the treacherous approaches of the Eccentric
Woodland, lies @@yRakuen@@N -- a city founded on the belief that a settlement
could be governed by beauty, abundance, and consensus rather than by
registries and force. Its founding document, the @@ySouthward Compact@@N,
was drafted as a deliberate rejection of Midgaard's ledger culture.

@@gThe Paradise Thesis@@N

Haven-Architect @@gElys Savan@@N and the founding coalition spent four years
drafting terms before anyone broke ground. The @@gParadise Thesis@@N argued
that a city built around shared surplus -- common orchards, cooperative
waterworks, rotating stewardship -- would generate greater loyalty and
lower enforcement costs than Midgaard's system of adjudicated obligations.
For a generation, it worked. The orchards took root, the cisterns flowed,
and the Festival of Ever-Bloom celebrated genuine prosperity.

@@yThe Five Eras@@N

In its @@yfounding generation@@N, Rakuen thrived as a small community of three
hundred settlers, exporting forest medicines and preserved fruit. During
the @@ystandardization century@@N, it appeared on official maps and its Garden
Ledger system drew admiring delegations from Kiess. The @@ycontainment era@@N
saw Midgaard quietly use Rakuen as a resettlement valve for inconvenient
persons. Then the @@yAsh-and-Iron decades@@N struck: black rain from the
Cinderteeth poisoned cisterns, killed orchards, and forced the paradise
city to adopt ration towers, labor drafts, and salvage courts -- every
emergency institution it had been founded to reject. The @@ymodern era@@N
is defined by the aftermath of three refused annexation petitions.

@@rThree Petitions, Three Refusals@@N

The @@rSouthmark Petition@@N argued mutual benefit and moral obligation.
Midgaard refused on grounds of incompatible accounting standards. The
@@rAsh Plea@@N opened with a death count and named specific offices that had
withheld relief. Midgaard refused on grounds of route instability. The
@@rIron Compact Appeal@@N -- nine years in drafting, co-signed by Mafdet's
Ledger Houses and certified by Kiess jurists -- proposed a twenty-five-year
incremental integration. Midgaard refused on constitutional grounds,
arguing that absorbing Rakuen would require dissolving its founding charter.

Each refusal remade the city's politics. Each deepened the factionalism.

@@dA City That Refuses to Be Governed@@N

Rakuen has refused every attempt by the five-city institutions to define it.
It is not a Midgaard district. It is not a sovereign power. It is a city
where the founding myth and daily reality wage a low-grade war on every
street corner -- where cracked Promise Stones still mark the boundaries
of a paradise that exists now only in ceremony, and where the Bloom
Pavilion's living roof of trained ivy is maintained as proof that
something, at least, still grows as the founders intended.

The Ember Wardens patrol the causeways. The Garden Ledger Clerks guard
records that contradict the official story. And Rakuen persists: proud,
exhausted, and ungovernable.
